{With his last move 13.h3 White has prepared a quick pawn attack based on g4
and f5. How can Black cross his intentions?} 13... Ng6 $1 {[%csl Gf4][%cal
Gh5h4] Attacking f4 and threatening the blockade ...h5-h4.} 14. Ne2 $2 ({
I thought} 14. g3 $5 {to be even worse on account of} h4 {, but the engines
surprised me with} 15. f5 exf5 16. g4 $1 Nce7 (16... fxg4 $2 17. e6 $1 $18 {
[%cal Gd3g6,Ge1e6]}) 17. Rdg1 Nf4 18. Qd2 Ne6 {With such a blocking knight
Black should be out of danger.} 19. Bxh4 fxg4 20. hxg4 O-O-O 21. Ng5 $5 (21.
Kb1 Kb7 $11) 21... Re8 $1 {This is an elegant and effective solution to the
threat Nxf7:} 22. Nxf7 Rxh4 23. Rxh4 Ng6 {[%csl Gf7,Gh4]}) ({The previously
played} 14. Ng5 $5 {did not cross my mind either:} Nxf4 (14... Be7 $2 15. Nxe6
$1 Qxe6 16. f5 Nf4 17. Qf3 $1 Qxf5 18. Nxd5 $16) 15. Qf3 Ng6 16. Rhf1 Nd8 17.
Bg3 h4 18. Bh2 c6 {White has serious pressure, but in the absence of pawn
breaks it is not obvious how he could make further progress. In fact, a
positional draw (as they would call it in a study; in mortal terms, it would
be "uneventful draw") is not improbable. One interesting aspect is that there
is no simple way to double rooks on the f-file.} 19. Rd2 $6 ({Even if prepared
with} 19. Kb1 {, doubling rooks does not work:} Rc8 20. Rd2 $6 {[%csl Gf1]} Be7
$1 21. Nxf7 O-O 22. Qh5 Nxf7 23. Qxg6 Nh8) 19... Be7 20. Nxf7 O-O $1 21. Qh5
Rxf7 22. Rxf7 Nxf7 23. Qxg6 Bg5 $19 {[%cal Gg5d2] 0-1 (38) Larsen,K (2300)
-Rustemov,A (2607) Copenhagen 2001}) 14... h4 $15 {I suspect that Kortschnoj
would attach an "-/+" or even "-+" and he may well be right. Actually, this is
how I evaluated the position during the game.} 15. Kb1 O-O-O 16. c4 $6 {
Opening the centre only increases White's problems,} dxc4 17. Qxc4 Nce7 18. Be3
Nd5 $6 {This allows White some unnecessary activity.} (18... Nf5 $1 19. Bc1
Nge7 $15 {/-/+}) 19. Bc1 Nge7 20. g4 $5 hxg3 21. Nxg3 $15 {And Black had to
fight hard to win.} 0-1

