1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 {This is more active than 3.Nd2 examined in the first
database, as it keeps the pressure on d5 and the queen's bishop's diagonal
open. But at the same time it is less flexible as after blocking the centre
with e4-e5 White rarely manages to consolidate his d4-pawn with c2-c3.} Bb4 {
This is the classical main line, which I still prefer to 3...Nf6, a move that
has become at least as popular lately. Black immediately renews the attack on
e4 and is ready to turn the position double-edged strategically after an
exchange on c3, yelding him the better structure at the price of increasing
the influence of the c1-bishop. According to the classical general rules, the
last move may seem a bit premature, as one is supposed to develop the knight
first and only then the bishop. In many lines White can try to take advantage
of the early weakening of the g7-square. But the threat against e4 is so
strong that in practice the last move has proved its viability along the
decades. This does not mean that White has not tried several ways to prove the
early bishop development premature. In fact there is a wide range of
alternatives to the absolute main line 4.e5. We will start by investigating
all these secondary lines before examining the main ones. In this section we
will mention a few of the less important sidelines, and then proceed by
looking at the "main side lines" one by one.} 4. Qd3 {White tries to activate
his queen quickly in order to put some pressure on the slightly weakened black
kingside. But as almost always, wasting time so early with the queen offers
Black adequate counterplay.} ({The rare} 4. f3 {deserves only brief mentioning.
} dxe4 5. a3 (5. fxe4 Qh4+ 6. Ke2 Bxc3 7. bxc3 Qxe4+) 5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 c5 {
with poor development and an unstable centre for White.}) (4. Be3 {tries to
combine the ideas of 4.a3 and 4.Qg4 examined below, but it is not dangerous.}
dxe4 5. Qg4 Nf6 6. Qxg7 Rg8 7. Qh6 Rg6 {This is the most active way to
highlight the drawbacks of 4.Be3. Unable to retreat on the diagonal c1-h6, the
queen is caged on the kingside, and black can already force a draw by
repitition if he desires.} ({But} 7... Nbd7 {is also playable.} 8. Bd2 Nb6 9.
Qe3 Bd7 10. O-O-O Bc6 11. f3 Bxc3 12. Qxc3 Qd5 13. Qa5 O-O-O 14. Qxd5 Rxd5 $15
{Gurgenidze,B (2445)-Eingorn,V (2525) Riga (Latvia) 1985 (0-1, 65)}) 8. Qh4 Rg4
9. Qh3 Nc6 10. Nge2 (10. O-O-O {Sokolova,V (2037)-Donskov,A (2062) Peterhof
2008 (1-0, 41)} Bxc3 $1 11. bxc3 Qd6 12. Ne2 Bd7 13. Kb2 Rg6 $17) 10... e5 11.
O-O-O Rg6 12. Qh4 Rg4 {and Black can force a draw if he wishes so.}) 4... dxe4
5. Qxe4 Nf6 6. Qh4 {This is the main idea behind White's system. He plans to
continue with Bg5, but the queen will soon prove exposed.} (6. Qd3 {is merely
a loss of time, as the queen returns to a square where it had been before,
while Black has made some progress in development.} c5 7. dxc5 O-O $11) 6...
Nc6 $5 {One of the possible plans. The knight is heading to f5 with gain of
time.} 7. Nf3 Ne7 8. Bd3 (8. Bg5 {leads to dynamic play despite simplfications:
} Nf5 9. Qf4 (9. Qh3 Qd5 10. Bd3 Nxd4 11. Nxd4 Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 Qxg5 $15) 9...
Nd5 10. Qxf5 exf5 11. Bxd8 Kxd8 12. Kd2 Be6 13. a3 Nxc3 (13... Bxc3+ 14. bxc3
Nb6 15. Bd3 Re8 16. Rhe1 f6 17. Rab1 Kd7 18. h4 g6 $11) 14. axb4 (14. bxc3 Bd6
$15) 14... Ne4+ 15. Ke1 Re8 {Black's initiative compensates for White's better
structure.}) 8... Nf5 9. Bxf5 exf5 10. Bg5 {The only attempt at questioning
Black's strategy. Facing the danger on c3, White also tries to cause some
structural damage.} (10. O-O Bxc3 11. bxc3 Ne4 12. Qxd8+ {1/2-1/2 Heberla,B 
(2500)-David,A (2602) Cappelle-la-Grande 2009} Kxd8 13. Ne5 Nd6 14. c4 (14. Ba3
Be6 $15 {о...f7-f6.}) 14... f6 15. c5 fxe5 16. cxd6 cxd6 17. dxe5 dxe5 18. Re1
Re8 19. Bb2 $11) 10... Qe7+ 11. Ne5 (11. Kf1 Bxc3 12. bxc3 Be6 13. Bxf6 gxf6
14. g3 O-O-O 15. Kg2 Bd5 $17) {Pablo Marin,A (2455)-Simon Padros,E (2335)
Spain 1999 (1/2-1/2, 34)} 11... Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 Qe6 13. O-O Ne4 14. Bc1 O-O $15
{Black has normal development and the more flexible structure.} *

