1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qg4 {A very direct attempt to use the
vulnerability of the g7-pawn. While pursuing the same aim, this is riskier
than 4.a3, as in the following lines the c3-knight will still be pinned.} Nf6
5. Qxg7 Rg8 6. Qh6 Rg6 7. Qe3 {The most popular move and the best chance for...
maintaining equality.} (7. Qh4 Nxe4 (7... Rg4 $11 {more or less forces a draw
since} 8. Qh3 e5 9. Qd3 Rxe4+ 10. Nge2 exd4 11. a3 {, as played in Benson,L 
(2039)-Peierl,W (1834) Opatija 2013 (1-0, 32), could have offered Black the
more pleasant position after} Ba5 12. b4 dxc3 13. bxa5 d4 $17) 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9.
Nge2 b6 $5 $11) (7. Qh3 $2 e5 8. Qd3 dxe4 9. Qb5+ Nc6 10. dxe5 a6 11. Qa4 {
Ishkinin,R (1662)-Nikolin,S Ufa 2012 (0-1, 15)} Nd5 12. Bd2 Nb6 13. Qb3 Be6 $19
) (7. Qf4 $6 Rg4 8. Qf3 Nc6 $15) 7... c5 {It turns out that the queen is not
entirely safe on e3 either.} 8. a3 (8. Bd2 Nc6 9. Bb5 (9. Nge2 Qb6 $5 $146 10.
dxc5 Bxc5 11. Qf4 e5 12. Qh4 Nb4 $17) 9... Bd7 10. Bxc6 Bxc6 11. Nge2 (11.
O-O-O {Panchenko,A-Steinberg,M Sukhumi 1971 (1/2, 58)} Ng4 12. Qe1 cxd4 13.
Nxd5 Bxd2+ 14. Rxd2 Bxd5 15. exd5 Qxd5 $15) 11... dxe4 12. dxc5 Ng4 13. Qd4 {
Planinec,A (2535)-Byrne,R (2600) Moscow 1975 (1-0, 39)} e3 14. Bxe3 Qxd4 15.
Nxd4 Bxg2 16. Rg1 Nxh2 $17) (8. e5 Nc6 9. Bb5 {Brandenburg,D (2200)-Tondivar,B
(2328) Leeuwarden 2003 (0-1, 29)} Qb6 10. a3 Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 Qxb5 12. exf6 Rxg2
$17) (8. Nge2 cxd4 $146 9. Nxd4 Nxe4 10. Bb5+ Bd7 11. O-O Bxc3 12. bxc3 e5 13.
Bxd7+ Nxd7 14. f3 exd4 15. cxd4 Qg5 16. Qe2 Qh5 17. Re1 Re6 18. fxe4 Qxe2 19.
Rxe2 Rxe4 20. Rxe4+ dxe4 $11 21. c4 $2 Nb6 22. c5 Nd5 $17) (8. exd5 Nxd5 9. Qd3
(9. Qe5 Nxc3 10. a3 Ba5 11. Qh8+ Ke7 12. Qxd8+ Kxd8 13. Bd2 cxd4 14. Ne2 Nxe2
15. Bxa5+ b6 16. Bxe2 Bb7 17. Bb4 Bxg2 18. Rg1 Bd5 19. O-O-O Nc6 $17) 9... cxd4
10. a3 (10. Qxd4 e5 11. Qd3 Nc6 12. Nge2 Nd4 13. Nxd4 exd4 14. Qxd4 Nxc3 15.
Qxd8+ Kxd8 16. a3 Ba5 $19) 10... Ba5 11. b4 Nxb4 12. axb4 Bxb4 13. Bd2 dxc3 14.
Qxd8+ Kxd8 $19 {Gavilan,A-Foguelman,A Buenos Aires 1951 (0-1, 56)}) 8... Ba5 {
Keeping the pressure on d4 and even threatening to increase it with ...Bb6.} (
8... cxd4 {is also good.} 9. Qxd4 Nc6 10. Qd3 Bxc3+ 11. Qxc3 Nxe4 12. Qh8+ Ke7
({The more restrictive move order is} 12... Kd7 $5 {, when White should
transpose to the game by exchanging queens, as after} 13. Qxh7 $2 {Black has}
Qf6 14. f3 Nd4 $40) 13. Qxd8+ ({White could try to exploit the previous
inaccuracy with} 13. Qxh7 $5 Qa5+ 14. c3 Nf6 15. Qh3 $13) 13... Kxd8 14. g3 {
Sanchez Jerez,E (2291)-Gromovs,S (2169) Calvia 2013 (1-0, 56)} e5 15. Bd3 Bf5
16. g4 Rxg4 17. f3 Rg2 18. fxe4 dxe4 19. Be2 Kc7 $44) 9. b4 (9. Bd2 Nc6 10. Bb5
{Miladinovic,I (2599)-Calandri,F (2115) Assisi 2003 (1-0, 28)} cxd4 11. Qxd4
Bd7 12. Bxc6 Bxc6 13. exd5 Bb6 14. Qd3 Nxd5 15. Nf3 Rxg2 $17) (9. Nge2 Nc6) {
Micottis,D (2074)-Giroyan,G (2385) Montbeliard 2014 (0-1, 29)} 9... cxd4 $146
10. Qxd4 Bb6 11. Qd3 Nxe4 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Qxd8+ (13. Qxe4 Qf6 $19) 13... Bxd8
14. Be3 a5 15. b5 Nd7 {With at least equal chances for black due to his better
