1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Bd2 {The legend goes that Alekhine invented
this move by accident in his game with Flohr, as he actually wanted to play 4.
e5 c5 5.Ld2. But this pawn sacrifice is very much in his style so the move
might have been intentional. White once again intends to attack g7, this time
without allowing the weaking of the queenside structure. The drawback of the
last move is that it does not do much to consolide the d4-pawn, which Black
can immediately take advantage of.} dxe4 5. Qg4 (5. Nxe4 {loses a pawn without
convincing compensation.} Qxd4 6. Bd3 (6. Nc3 Nf6 7. Nf3 Qd8 8. Bd3 O-O 9. O-O
b6 10. Qe2 Bb7 $15) 6... Bxd2+ 7. Qxd2 Qxb2 $1 ({The aforementioned game went} 
7... Qd8 $6 8. O-O-O {with advance in development and excellent compensation
for the pawn in Alekhine,A-Flohr,S Nottingham 1936 (1-0, 57).}) 8. Rd1 Nf6 9.
Bb5+ Nfd7 10. Nc3 a6 11. Bd3 O-O 12. Nf3 Nc6 13. O-O Qb4 14. Rfe1 Nf6 15. Ng5
h6 16. Nge4 Qe7 $17 {White has no compensation for the missing pawns, Stocek,J
(2470)-Tibensky,R (2420) Litomysl 1997 (1/2-1/2, 65)}) (5. Nge2 Nf6 6. Nxe4
Bxd2+ 7. Nxd2 b6 8. c3 Bb7 9. Nf4 {Defending g2 in order to prepare the
bishop's development. In Chemes, L-Dodero, E Santa Fe 1956 (0-1, 56), Black
could have taken over the initiative with} O-O 10. Be2 c5 11. dxc5 Qc7 $15)
5... Qxd4 {Grabbing a second pawn and defending g7 on the way.} 6. Nf3 {
The most active move, immediately gaining time on the black queen.} (6. O-O-O
f5 7. Qh4 Be7 8. Bg5 (8. Qg3 Bd6 9. Bf4 Bxf4+ 10. Qxf4 Qc5 11. f3 Nf6 12. fxe4
e5 13. Qg5 O-O 14. exf5 Nc6 15. g4 Nd4 16. Bg2 Bd7 $15 {Lehmann,H (2239)
-Reutsky,S (2360) Pardubice 2007 (0-1, 21)}) 8... Bxg5+ 9. Qxg5 Qf6 10. Qg3 Ne7
11. Qxc7 O-O $17) (6. Nge2 Qf6 7. O-O-O Qg6 8. Qh3 Nf6 9. Nf4 Qg4 10. Qe3 O-O
11. Be2 Qg5 $13 12. a3 $2 Bc5 13. h4 Qe5 14. Qg3 Nc6 $17 {Grabarczyk,B (2439)
-Haba,P (2497) Germany 2000 (0-1, 23)}) 6... h5 ({This is slightly more
accurate than} 6... Nh6 {, when the simplifying line still offers White some
chances of a light advantage on account of the passive h6-knight:} 7. Qxe6+
Bxe6 8. Nxd4 Bd7 9. O-O-O $5 {with better development for White who can
probably retrieve the e4-pawn soon.} (9. Nxe4 Bxd2+ 10. Nxd2 Nc6 11. Nxc6 Bxc6
{1/2-1/2 Sax,G (2575) -Farago,I (2525) Budapest 1984})) 7. Qxe6+ (7. Qf4 Qd6 8.
Qxe4 Nf6 9. Qh4 Nc6 10. O-O-O Qe7 11. Qg3 (11. a3 Bxc3 12. Bxc3 Bd7 13. Bc4
O-O-O 14. Rhe1 Kb8 {offers Black just reasonable compensation for the pawn as
he has no real weaknesses and is well developed.}) 11... Bd7 12. Nb5 Bxd2+ 13.
Nxd2 O-O 14. Qxc7 Rfc8 15. Qd6 a6 16. Qxe7 Nxe7 17. Nd6 Rc7 $15 {Grabarczyk,B 
(2394) -Gdanski,J (2535) Plock 2000 (0-1, 53)}) 7... Bxe6 8. Nxd4 Bd7 9. O-O-O
(9. Nxe4 Bxd2+ 10. Nxd2 Nc6 11. N2f3 O-O-O 12. O-O-O Nh6 13. h3 Nf5 $11 {
Arnason, A-Levitt,J (2465) Reykjavik 1990 (1/2-1/2, 38)}) 9... Nf6 $11 {
This is a move Black would be missing if he had played 6...Nh6.} 10. Bc4 {
Velimirovic,D-Ivkov, B Zenica 1963 (0-1, 32)} (10. Nxe4 Bxd2+ 11. Nxd2 O-O $11)
10... Nc6 11. Nxc6 Bxc6 12. Nxe4 Bxd2+ 13. Nxd2 h4 $5 14. Rhe1+ Kf8 $11 {
followed by ...Rh5 or ... Rh6 with pleasant counterplay.} *

