1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 {This is already a more consistent way of
trying to exploit the weakness on g7. It can lead to interesting play but
objectively should not be a problem for Black.} Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 dxe4 6. Qg4 Nf6
7. Qxg7 Rg8 8. Qh6 Bd7 $5 {A relatively rare but in my opinion very
interesting move. The usual plan is based on ...Nbd7, ...c7-c5 and ...b7-b6.
The last move keeps the possibility of ...c7-c5 without obstructing the
queen's access to a5 and exposing the b-pawn to a4-a5.} 9. Ne2 {In this line
the knight has to struggle a bit before reaching a good square.} ({The untested
} 9. Rb1 {fails to provoke ...b7-b6:} Ba4 (9... Bc6 $5 10. Ne2 Nbd7) 10. Rxb7
Nbd7 11. Nh3 c5 12. dxc5 Bc6 13. Rb4 Qe7 14. Be3 Rg6 15. Qf4 {Black is well
regrouped and can force a draw by repetition if he wishes so:} e5 ({Taking the
exchange with} 15... Nd5 {may be double-edged.}) 16. Qh4 Rg4 $11) ({The
alternate way of developing the knight is} 9. Nh3 {but this leaves d4
vulnerable.} c5 $146 {The logical reaction in the centre.} 10. Be2 Nc6 11. O-O
cxd4 ({A more restrictive move order than} 11... Rg6 12. Qh4 cxd4 13. f3 {
, with chances to take over the initiative.}) 12. f3 e3 $1 13. Bd3 e5 (13...
Qe7 14. cxd4) 14. Rb1 Nd5 15. Qxh7 Ke7 (15... Nce7 16. cxd4 Qc7 17. c4 Bxh3 18.
cxd5 Bxg2 19. Bxe3 Bxf1+ 20. Kxf1 a6) 16. Rxb7 (16. cxd4 Rh8 17. Qe4 Nc3 18.
Qxe3 Nxb1 19. d5 Bxh3 20. dxc6 Qb6 $15 {with an extra exchange and chances to
extinguish White's light initiative.}) 16... Qc8 17. Ba6 Rh8 18. Qd3 Rb8 19.
Rxa7 Qd8 {with a messy position and mutual chances.}) ({The pinning} 9. Bg5 {
is not dangerous and in fact leaves the queenside vulnerable, something which
does not happen in the lines with ...b7-b6.} Rg6 10. Qh4 c5 $5 $146 11. Rb1 (
11. Nh3 $2 cxd4 $15 12. Nf4 Qa5 $19) (11. Ne2 {transposes to the main line.})
11... Bc6 12. Nh3 Nbd7 13. Nf4 Rxg5 14. Qxg5 Qa5 15. Ne2 O-O-O $15 {With more
than enough compensation for the pawn, as Black is perfectly developed and
White's queenside is weak.}) 9... c5 10. Bg5 (10. dxc5 {weakens the structure
without promising much initiative in exchange.} Na6 11. c6 (11. Be3 e5 12. h3
Rg6 13. Qh4 Qa5 $15) 11... Bxc6 12. Nd4 Ba4 13. Rb1 Nc5 14. Bb5+ (14. Bg5 Ng4
15. Bxd8 Nxh6 16. Bc7 Ke7 $11) 14... Bxb5 15. Rxb5 {Rombaldoni,A (2484)-L'Ami,
