1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nge2 {A constructive developing move,
indirectly defending e4. It tends to lead to simplifications but not
necessarily to a forced draw.} dxe4 5. a3 Bxc3+ {Black opts for rapid
development, without wasting time by retreating the bishop. This policy will
offer him enough activity to compensate for the potentially strong
dark-squared bishop.} ({The main alternative is} 5... Be7 6. Nxe4 Nf6 {, but
the main line move offers Black clearer ways to equalize.}) 6. Nxc3 Nc6 {
Black develops with gain of time, setting up pressure in the centre.} ({
The greedy} 6... f5 {famously led to problems on dark squares after} 7. f3 {
Alekhine, A-Nimzowitsch,A Bled 1931 MainBase [ChessBase] (1-0, 19)}) 7. Bb5 ({
This is more active than} 7. Be3 Nf6 8. Qd2 Ne7 {Preparing ...Bd7-c6 and also .
..Nf5 or ...Nd5.} 9. Bg5 ({It is better to activate the bishop at once as after
} 9. O-O-O Bd7 10. Bg5 Bc6 {Black manages to consolide his extra pawn without
making any concession.} 11. Bc4 Qd6 12. Rhe1 O-O-O 13. g3 Ned5 14. Nxe4 Nxe4
15. Rxe4 Nb6 16. d5 Nxc4 17. Rxc4 Qxd5 $17 {Van Mil,J (2435)-Kortschnoj,V 
(2605) Netherlands 1993 (1/2-1/2, 69)}) 9... Ned5 10. O-O-O Bd7 11. Bc4 Bc6 12.
Rhe1 Nxc3 13. Qxc3 Nd5 14. Qg3 Qd6 15. Qh4 Nb6 (15... Ne7 $5 16. Bxe7 Qxe7 17.
Qxe7+ Kxe7 18. d5 Bxd5 19. Bxd5 exd5 20. Rxd5 Rhe8 $11 {Psakhis}) 16. Bf1 f6
17. Bf4 {Van Mil,J (2415)-Rozentalis,E (2575) Berlin 1991 (1-0, 34)} Qd7 {
The best queen retreat. If White plays in a similar way as in the game,} 18.
Qh5+ g6 19. Qa5 {, Black has} Qd5 20. Qxd5 Nxd5 21. Bg3 O-O-O $15 22. Rxe4 $2
Nc3) (7. d5 {leads to a different type of position and is examined in the next
line.}) 7... Nge7 8. Bg5 (8. Nxe4 O-O {leaves White underdeveloped and hanging
in the centre.} 9. c3 (9. Be3 $2 f5 10. Ng5 f4 11. Bd2 Qd5 12. Bxc6 Nxc6 $15
13. Qh5 h6 14. h4 Qf5 $5 $19 {Costello,C-Watson,J (2420) Hastings 1987 (0-1,
27)}) 9... e5 10. dxe5 (10. Bxc6 Nxc6 11. d5 Ne7 12. c4 f5 13. Nc3 f4 14. f3
Nf5 15. O-O {In Horvath,T-Knaak,R (2495) Trnava 1981 (1/2-1/2, 36) Black
played 15... Rf6, but this could have caused problems with the e5-pawn after
16.Re1. A more harmonious way to prepare the kingside attack was} a5 $5 16. Re1
Re8 17. Rb1 Ra6 $15) 10... Qxd1+ 11. Kxd1 Nxe5 12. Bf4 N7g6 13. Be3 Bg4+ 14.
Kc2 a6 15. Bf1 Bf5 16. f3 Rfe8 17. Re1 Rad8 {, with at least equal play for
Black in Bronstein,D-Bondarevsky,I Leningrad (Russia) 1947 (1/2-1/2, 34)}) 8...
f6 9. Be3 O-O 10. Qd2 f5 11. f3 (11. O-O-O {offers Black an important tempo
for development.} Nd5 ({Less good is} 11... a6 {, which wastes the offered
tempo for nothing.} 12. Bxc6 Nxc6 13. f3 {with excellent compensation on the
dark squares.}) 12. Nxd5 (12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. Nxd5 Qxd5 14. Kb1 Rb8 15. Bf4 e5
16. Bxe5 Be6 17. b3 c5 $15) 12... Qxd5 ({More active than} 12... exd5 13. Bxc6
