1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nge2 dxe4 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. Nxc3 Nc6 7. d5 $5 {
In his book "French Defence 3.Nc3 Bb4" Psakhis expresses his surprize when
noticing that this move has become popular lately. Indeed, White seems to be
helping Black to complete his development, but in doing so he hopes to open
the position for his bishops. It turns out that Black's activity is just
enough to keep the bishops under control or exchange one of them by force.}
exd5 8. Qxd5 (8. Nxd5 $2 Be6 $17) 8... Be6 {The most logical move, enabling
the rook to recapture on d8.} 9. Qxe4 (9. Qxd8+ Rxd8 10. Nxe4 Nd4 {offers
Black a strong initiative in the centre.} 11. Bd3 Bc4 $5 12. O-O ({White does
not seem to be able to trap the knight after} 12. Bxc4 Nxc2+ 13. Ke2 Nxa1 {
, for instance} 14. Rd1 Ne7 15. Rxd8+ Kxd8 16. Ng5 Kd7 17. Nxf7 Re8 18. Ne5+
Kc8 $15 {with good chances to convert the extra exchange.}) 12... Bxd3 13. cxd3
Nb3 14. Rb1 Ne7 $15 {Landenbergue,C (2415)-Rozentalis,E (2575) Chiasso 1991 
(0-1, 56)}) 9... Nf6 10. Qh4 {The most popular move, in the spirit of the 4.
Qd3 variation examined above, aiming to get some pressure with Bg5. But
White's poor development prevents him from claiming an advantage. The same
goes for the alternatives.} (10. Qa4 O-O {White faces a tough choice about how
to continue his development.} 11. Bd3 (11. Be3 Ng4) (11. Be2 Nd4 12. Bd3 b5 13.
Nxb5 Nb3 $1 $17) 11... Ne5 12. Be2 Qe8 13. Qxe8 Rfxe8 14. O-O Bf5 {and White
might have to sacrifice the c2-pawn for unclear compensation.}) (10. Qf4 Nd5
11. Qg3 (11. Nxd5 Qxd5 12. Bd3 {Otherwise White may well not be able to
develop his kingside.} Qxg2 13. Be4 Qh3 14. Qxc7 O-O 15. Rg1 Bf5 16. Rg3 Qh5
17. Rg5 Qh3 $11 18. Rxf5 Rae8 19. Qf4 Qg2 $15) 11... Nxc3 12. Qxc3 Qd4 ({
Another possibility is} 12... Qd5 13. Be3 O-O-O 14. f3 {The only way to
develop his kingside.} f6 15. Be2 Nd4 $11 16. Rd1 Nxe2 17. Rxd5 $2 Nxc3 18.
Rxd8+ Rxd8 19. bxc3 Bf5 $17) 13. Bd2 (13. Qxd4 Nxd4 14. Bd3 O-O-O 15. Be3 Bf5
16. O-O-O Nb3+ $1 $11) 13... Qe4+ 14. Be3 O-O-O 15. f3 Qh4+ 16. Bf2 Qg5 17. Be3
Qh4+ 18. Bf2 Qg5 19. h4 Qg6 20. Be3 Qg3+ 21. Bf2 Qg6 $11 {, with a probable
draw by repetition.}) 10... Qe7 11. Be2 (11. Be3 O-O-O 12. Bb5 Nd5 13. Qxe7
Ndxe7 14. Rd1 a6 15. Be2 Nf5 $11 {Panagiotopoulos,A (1975)-Kallitsis,N (1700)
Chania 2003 (1/2-1/2, 28)}) 11... O-O-O 12. Be3 Nd5 13. Qxe7 Ndxe7 14. O-O (14.
g4 $6 h5 15. gxh5 Nf5 16. Bg5 f6 17. Bd2 Ncd4 18. O-O-O Nxe2+ 19. Nxe2 Bd5 20.
Rhg1 Bf3 21. Rde1 Bxe2 22. Rxe2 Rxh5 $15 {Gaponenko,I (2411)-Kononenko,T (2388)
Antalya 2002 (1/2-1/2, 48)}) (14. Bd2 Nd4 15. Bd3 Ng6 $11) 14... Nd4 (14... Nf5
$5 $15) 15. Bxd4 Rxd4 16. Rfd1 $11 {1/2-1/2 Rogulj,B (2386)-Zaja,I (2467)
