1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. exd5 exd5 {In practice this line has many
times proven unpleasant for Black. White hopes to reach an improved version of
the Exchange variation (to be examined in the next database) as Black has
comitted his king's bishop already. Generally White's main hopes are connected
with setting up some light kingside pressure, which could eventually result
into an attack or some other type of advantage. Objectively the line is not
dangerous, but Black should know what he is doing. For this repertoire I have
chosen the most ambitious setup, leading to strategically double-edged play.}
5. Bd3 {This is the main line, continuing the natural course of development
and targeting the kingside already.} ({The early queen development} 5. Qf3 {
is abstractly premature and is inoffensive from a practical point of view.} Nc6
6. Bb5 (6. Nge2 Qe7 $5 $146 7. Qe3 Ba5 8. a3 Nf6 9. Qxe7+ Nxe7 10. Bg5 c6 $11
11. Bxf6 gxf6 12. Ng3 h5 13. h4 Bc7 14. Be2 Bxg3 15. fxg3 Nf5) 6... Nge7 7.
Nge2 (7. Bf4 O-O 8. O-O-O Be6 9. Nge2 Qd7 10. h3 a6 11. Bxc6 Nxc6 12. g4 b5 13.
Rhg1 Rfb8 14. Ng3 Bf8 15. Nh5 Kh8 16. g5 b4 17. Ne2 {Mestrovic,Z-Uhlmann,W
Sarajevo 1965 (0-1, 27)} a5 $17) 7... Bf5 8. Bd3 Qd7 9. Bf4 Bg4 10. Qe3 O-O-O
11. f3 Bf5 12. O-O-O Rhe8 13. Qf2 Bxd3 14. Rxd3 Na5 $11 {Tukhaev,A (2517)
-Bartel,M (2608) Warsaw 2007 (1/2-1/2, 66)}) (5. Nge2 {delays the bishop's
development and offers Black some time to get coordinated.} Nf6 6. a3 Be7 7.
Ng3 O-O 8. Bd3 b6 $5 9. O-O c5 10. Bg5 Be6 $11) ({The neutral} 5. Nf3 {offers
Black easy play.} Nf6 6. Bd3 Qe7+ 7. Be3 Ng4 8. O-O Nxe3 9. fxe3 Qxe3+ 10. Kh1
Bxc3 11. bxc3 O-O 12. Ne5 g6 $5 $146 {With just some compensation for the pawn.
}) 5... Nc6 {This is one of the main lines for Black and the most ambitious
one, as it speeds up the development without committing his intentions
regarding the king.} ({Neutral play such as} 5... Nf6 6. Nge2 O-O 7. O-O c6 {
is sound enough, but tends to leave White with some kingside initiative.}) 6.
Nf3 {This exposes the knight to an effective pin.} (6. Be3 Nge7 7. Qf3 Be6 8.
Nge2 Qd7 9. h3 Bf5 {doesn't face Black with problems either.}) ({The main
alternatives} 6. a3) ({and} 6. Nge2 {are examined separately in the next two
lines.}) 6... Bg4 7. O-O Nge7 {Black has a complex regrouping in mind based on
...Qd7, ...Nd8 and the bishop's retreat to the h2-b8 diagonal.} 8. a3 (8. Ne2
Bxf3 9. gxf3 Bd6 $15 {speeds up Black's regrouping with respect to the main
line.}) (8. Be3 Qd7 9. a3 (9. Nb5 a6 10. c3 axb5 11. cxb4 Nxb4 $15) (9. h3 Bh5
{maintains the pin and brings the bishop closer to g6.}) 9... Bxc3 10. bxc3 O-O
11. Re1 Rfe8 12. h3 Bf5 13. Ne5 Nxe5 14. dxe5 Rad8 (14... Nc6 15. f4 Bxd3 16.
Qxd3 Na5 17. Bd4 {1/2-1/2 Radulov,I-Uhlmann,W Havana 1969}) 15. f4 Bxd3 16.
cxd3 (16. Qxd3 Ng6 17. Rad1 c5 $132) 16... d4 17. Bxd4 b6 $11) 8... Ba5 9. Ne2
{White does not get anywhere without this regrouping. I remember that some
time ago my friend and French specialist GM Arizmendi mentioned the game
quoted below, adding that computers tend to be very optimistic from Wite's
point of view, completely without reasons. Things did not change much in the
meantime and the correct assessment stands: Black has at least equal play.}
Bxf3 10. gxf3 Qd7 11. c3 (11. Be3 Nf5 12. c3 Nce7 {with a harmonious
regrouping.}) 11... Nd8 12. Ng3 O-O (12... c6 {may be a more precise move
order.} 13. Re1 g6 14. Bh6 Ne6 15. f4 O-O-O 16. f5 Nxf5 17. Nxf5 gxf5 18. Bxf5
Rhg8+ 19. Kh1 Bc7 20. Qh5 Kb8 21. Rg1 Qd6 $11) 13. Re1 c6 14. Qc2 Kh8 15. Bxh7
$2 (15. f4 $1 {may offer White some pressure, since} f5 16. Nxf5 {loses a pawn.
}) 15... g6 16. Bg5 Ne6 17. Bf6+ Kxh7 18. Re5 Nf4 19. Qd2 Nh3+ 20. Kh1 Ng8 21.
Rh5+ gxh5 22. Qc2+ Kh6 $19 {Starostits,I (2456)-Arizmendi Martinez,J (2568)
Porto Carras 2011 (0-1, 27)} *

