1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. exd5 exd5 5. Bd3 Nc6 6. a3 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 {
This is doubtlessly the main line of the improved exchange variation, leading
to an interesting strategic struggle. White's bishops' pair is potentially
dangerous and the pawn break c3-c4 may offer him some initiative if carried
out after some necessary preparation. But Black can fight against these
dangers by exchanging the light-squared bishops, even though this can
sometimes cost him a pawn. In this case the remaining bishop will turn into a
"bad" one and the white central structure will remain weak.} Nge7 {With the
obvious idea of ... Bf5.} 8. Qf3 ({One essential element is that} 8. Qh5 {
can be safely met with} g6 {Black takes f5 under control with gain of time and
analysis shows that White does not have enough development to make use of the
weaknesses on dark squares.} 9. Qf3 (9. Qh6 Bf5 10. Qg7 (10. Nf3 Bxd3 11. cxd3
Nf5 12. Qf4 Qe7+ 13. Be3 O-O-O $15 {Rabiega,R (2527)-Heinrich,T (2290)
playchess.com INT 2004 (1-0, 40)}) 10... Rg8 11. Qxh7 Qd7 12. Ne2 O-O-O 13. Qh6
(13. O-O Rh8 14. Qg7 Bxd3 15. cxd3 Qe6 16. Nf4 Qf5 17. f3 Rdg8 18. g4 Rxg7 19.
gxf5 gxf5+ 20. Kh1 Rgh7 21. Ra2 Kd7) 13... g5 14. O-O Bxd3 15. cxd3 f5 16. Bxg5
Rh8 17. Qg7 Rdg8 $11) (9. Qe2 {Ovetchkin,R (2385)-Kaminski,M (2525) Koszalin
1996 (1/2-1/2, 28)} O-O 10. Nf3 Bf5 11. O-O Bxd3 12. cxd3 Nf5 13. Bf4 f6 $11 {
, with comfortable play.}) 9... Bf5 10. Rb1 b6 11. Ne2 Qd7 12. Bg5 (12. O-O
Bxd3 13. cxd3 Qf5 14. Bf4 g5 15. Bxc7 Qxf3 16. gxf3 Rc8 17. Be5 Rg8 18. Rfc1
Rg6 {, followed by ... f7-f6, with a strategically promising position despite
the missing pawn.}) 12... h6 $1 13. Bf4 (13. Bf6 O-O 14. O-O Qd6 15. Bxe7 Nxe7
$11) 13... O-O-O (13... g5 14. Be5 Nxe5 15. dxe5 {Negi,P (2651)-Farid,F (2369)
Manila 2013 (1-0, 38)} O-O-O $11) 14. O-O (14. Be5 Be4 15. Bxe4 Nxe5 16. Qg3
Nc4 $17) 14... f6 $15) ({The insertion of} 8. Rb1 b6 {mainly helps Black to
consolidate.} 9. Qf3 Be6 10. Ne2 Qd7 11. Ng3 Bg4 (11... O-O 12. h3 Na5 13. Nh5
f6 14. O-O Ng6 $11) (11... O-O-O {makes less sense than in a similar position
from the main line, as the king is more exposed here. Instead, after castling
short as recommended below, the move ...b7-b6 will prove useful.}) 12. Qf4 (12.
Qe3 O-O 13. h3 Bf5 $11) 12... Ng6 13. Qe3+ {Aravindh,C (2564)-Paehtz,T (2356)
Douglas 2016 (1-0, 43)} Nce7 14. h3 Be6 15. O-O O-O 16. Qf3 c5 $1 {Now is the
time for Black to make use of his previous ...b7-b6, while White's Rb1 does
not seem very useful.} 17. dxc5 bxc5 18. Be3 c4 19. Bxg6 fxg6 20. Qe2 Nc6 21.
Qd2 h6 $11) (8. Ne2 Bf5 9. Ng3 Bxd3 10. cxd3 Qd7 11. Qf3 O-O 12. O-O Ng6 13.
Nh5 f6 14. a4 Rf7 15. Rb1 b6 16. Re1 Rd8 17. Ba3 a5 $11 {Bellini,F (2501)
-Cheparinov,I (2634) Amsterdam 2005 (0-1, 44)}) 8... Be6 9. Ne2 Qd7 {Black
displays a maximum of flexibility, making all the useful moves before deciding
on which wing he is going to get castled. In principle, the queenside is the
safest residence for the king, but under certain circumstances it could also
go short.} 10. Ng3 (10. O-O O-O-O $1 (10... Bf5 11. Ng3 Bxd3 12. cxd3 {leaves
the f7-pawn hanging if Black intends to castle long.}) 11. h3 Bf5 12. Ng3 Bxd3
13. cxd3 Rdf8 {Defending the pawn and preparing a major kingside attack.} 14.
Re1 Rhg8 (14... f5 $5 15. Nh5 Rhg8 16. Ra2 f4 17. Qg4 g5 $13 {Senff,M (2476)
-Ivanov,S (2534) Moscow 2006 (0-1, 33)}) 15. Ra2 f5 16. Rae2 f4 17. Nf1 g5 18.
Nh2 Nf5 19. Qg4 $6 (19. Qh5 $11) 19... Qf7 20. Re6 h5 21. Qf3 Rd8 22. Qe2 Ng7
$17 {Marchena Hurtado,J (2294)-Suarez Gomez,J (2400) Salobrena 2015 (0-1, 74)})
