1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e5 {This is doubtlessly the only chance for
White to retain an opening advantage. But after the centre has stabilized
Black can also define his plans.} b6 $5 {I have developed a sympathy for this
move after seeing it in games of Kortschnoj and Petrosian, who used it on a
few occasions. Bronstein also had it in his repertoire, while Vaganian played
it a lot. The main attraction exerted by this system is that concrete theory
tends to be less important than positional understanding, something to be
treasured nowadays. The obvious main idea is to exchange the "bad" bishop with
...Ba6, but Black usually does this only after White has moved with his king's
bishop. At the same time Black may choose to preserve his dark-squared bishop
with ...Bf8. In several lines, Black can switch to ...c7-c5 without fearing
that White gets control over d4. Since Black has a choice on virtually every
step in the early phase it is useful to explain when each typical move is
indicated and when not. As a general rule, he should make some progress in
development before playing committal pawn moves. Against f2-f4, Black usually
reacts with ...h7-h5 and Ne7(h6)-f5, possibly in a reversed order. This plan
is likely to slow down White’s pawn attack, yielding Black some stability
until he makes progress with his queenside play. But with a White pawn on f2,
h7-h5 usually counts as an unnecessary weakness. White can set up a strong
pressure with for instance Bg5, Ne2-f4 and Re1-e3-f3. This would most likely
force ...g7-g6, making things even worse. There are exceptions to the latter
rule when Black needs to consolidate the knight on f5, on condition he had
exchanged the light-squared bishops and had distracted White’s pieces on
some other board sector. If White refrains from f2-f4, ...h7-h6 is more
typical. This not only prevents Bg5 or Ng5, but also prepares...g7-g5 in
positions with opposite castles.  Breaking with ...f7-f6 requires some
concrete evaluation of the mutual development progress. More concretely, Black
must make sure the e6-pawn would not be hanging after exf6. It is also
essential to understand whether...fxe5 is a real threat (or, alternatively, ...
g7-g5). The closely related...f7-f5 implies some further aspects.
Strategically, this is not without risk, as it offers White chances for
blocking the kingside with h3-h4 and Nc3-e2. Nevertheless, if Black castles
long and White castles short, this pawn advance more or less ensures Black
chances for a kingside attack based on ...g7-g5, sometimes (after h2-h4 mainly)
implying a pawn sacrifice. Evaluating the development progress is also
essential when planning ...c7-c5. Black has to count with dxc5 followed by a
sacrifice on d5 or some other dynamic ideas. If White castles long and his
kingside progress is not obvious, Black can be successful with a brutal attack
based on ...c5-c4 followed by ...b5-b4. In other cases Black could carry out
general exchanges on d4 if he has the knights on f5 and c6, especially if he
has previously succeeded in exchanging the light-squared bishops. If Black has
exchanged the light-squared bishops with ...Ba6xd3, but experiences some delay
in development, it makes sense to complete his queenside development with ...
Nc6, ...Qd7 (the optimal square for the queen in most cases), ... 0-0-0 and
only then prepare ...c7-c5 with ...Na5. But if White castles short, he should
consider the alternative kingside plans explained above.} ({The main line is
of course} 4... c5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 {, but in these lines theory has
developed heavily over the decades.}) {We will start by examining a few
sidelines and then switch to the main ones.} 5. Bd2 {This ensures White
against doubled pawns on the queenside, but is a bit slow.} (5. Nf3 {blocks
the queen's access to g4, allowing Black to continue his kingside development
with} Ne7 {, as the ...Bf8 retreat is not necessary anymore.} 6. a3 (6. Bd2 {
transposes below}) 6... Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 Ba6 8. Bxa6 Nxa6 9. Qd3 (9. O-O c5 {
ia also comfortable for Black.}) 9... Nb8 10. O-O (10. c4 c5 $5 $146 11. dxc5
bxc5 12. O-O Nbc6 $11) 10... c5 11. a4 Nd7 12. Ba3 Rc8 13. Rfd1 O-O 14. a5 h6
15. Qe2 Re8 16. h4 Nc6 17. axb6 axb6 18. Bc1 f6 19. exf6 {1/2-1/2 Geller,
E-Spassky,B Sukhumi 1968} Qxf6 $11) ({The seemingly active} 5. f4 {offers
Black the idea of playing for a blockade on light squares.} Ne7 6. Nf3 c5 7.
Bd2 Bxc3 8. Bxc3 Ba6 9. Bxa6 Nxa6 10. Qe2 Nb8 11. Qf2 Nd7 $11) (5. Qg4 Bf8 {and
}) (5. a3 Bf8 {are examined in detail in the next lines.}) 5... Ne7 6. f4 {
I have faced this move in practice. White does not achieve much by restricting
his dark-squared bishop.} (6. Nf3 Bxc3 $5 {Openly aiming for a good knight
versus a bad bishop ending.} 7. Bxc3 a5 {Preparing to play ...Ba6 with all
comfort, but also restricting the c3-bishop.} 8. h4 Qd7 9. h5 h6 10. Bd2 Ba6
11. Bxa6 Nxa6 12. O-O a4 13. Nh4 c5 14. Qg4 Rg8 15. c3 Nc7 16. Be3 {Black has
achieved certain strategic goals with the minor piece exchanges in the
previous phase of the game, but is slightly underdeveloped and faces some
problems maintaining the tension in the centre. Yasser's next move must have
come as a surprize to his legendary opponent.} c4 $1 {With the a-pawn just one
step back, whis could be considered the start of the standard attack based on .
..b6-b5-b4. The way it is, it allows White to freeze the queenside:} 17. a3 $6
{Geller wrongly assumed that he would have the better chances if the fight was
restricted to one wing only.} ({I It would have been wiser to keep both wings
under tension with, say,} 17. Rab1 {, when Black would have to permanently
take b2-b3 into consideration. This would have made castling long a risky
business.}) 17... O-O-O $1 {Phillidor may not have considered ensuring the
kings' safety as part of the pawns' task, but his axiom maintains its validity
in the current position. White's space advantage will turn against him as a
boomerang, making pawn contacts and the subsequent opening of the kingside
inevitable and offering Black excellent attacking chances precisely on White
traditional territory.} 18. Rae1 {Hoping for a slow regrouping with Bd2,
Re3-f3, but Black will be faster.} Nf5 19. Qh3 (19. Nxf5 exf5 {would kill any
white hope for a successful f4-f5 and clear the excellent blockading e6-square
for the knight.}) 19... g5 $1 {Under different circumstances (with the white
king on b1, for instance), this would leave Black with chronic pawn weaknesses.
The way it is, the pawns gladly display their natural tendency to advance 
(described by Nimzovich in a suggestive way) before being blocked, since their
eventual loss would clear files for the attack.} 20. hxg6 fxg6 21. Nf3 ({
Once again, the exchange} 21. Nxf5 exf5 {plays into Black's hands. Pawn
grabbing offers little joy:} 22. Qxh6 Ne6 {followed by ...Qf7 and ...Rh8. The
extra pawn does not make itself felt and the attack along the h-file will
become dangerous.}) 21... g5 {White faces concrete problems already: His most
active pieces from just a few moves ago are threatened with a fork.} 22. g4 {
Aiming to push the knight back and leave Black with a backward pawn on h6.} ({
White's hopes for a blockade with} 22. Nh2 {followed by Qh5 and Ng4 prove
illusory after} h5 $1 $17 23. Qxh5 $2 Rh8 {, soon followed by ...Qh7.}) ({Or if
} 22. Qh5 g4 23. Nh4 Nxh4 24. Qxh4 Rdf8 $17 {planning ...Rf5, ...h6-h5, with
excellent play on the light squares, when pawn grabbing once again has fatal
consequences:} 25. Qxh6 Rh8 26. Qg6 Rfg8 27. Qc2 Qf7 {followed by ...Qh5.})
22... h5 $1 {The perfect illustration of Nimzovitsch's views.} 23. Nxg5 (23.
gxf5 {would lead to a strategically interesting position if the white king was
on some other area of the board, but the way it is Black gets a strong attack:}
g4 24. Qh2 gxf3+ 25. Kh1 exf5 26. Rg1 Ne6 {followed by ...Rg4 soon. The point
is that taking the h5-pawn is unthinkable.}) 23... hxg4 {Strategically, the
most natural decision, aiming to prove the superiority of the knight over the
bishop.} (23... Nxe3 24. Qxe3 hxg4 {was an interesting alternative, though:}
25. f4 $8 gxf3 26. Rxf3 Qg7 27. Rg3 {/\Ne4} Qg6 {/\Rh8, Rdg8, Rh4, Qh5}) 24.
Qxg4 Rh8 25. f4 Rh4 26. Qg2 Rdh8 27. Rf3 Qg7 28. Bf2 R4h5 29. Bg3 Qg6 30. Bf2
Qg7 31. Bg3 R8h6 32. Kf2 Nxg3 33. Qxg3 Rh2+ 34. Ke3 Qg6 35. f5 exf5 36. Qf4 {
The white king is in dire straights, but Black misses the decisive blow now.}
Ne6 (36... Rxb2 $2 37. Qxf5+ Qxf5 38. Rxf5 {, and White managed to save the
game in Geller,E (2575)-Seirawan,Y (2575) London 1982 (1/2-1/2, 51)}) 37. Nxe6
R6h4 38. Qxh2 (38. Qxf5 Re4+) 38... Rxh2 39. Nf4 Qg5 40. Rb1 Kd7 {Zugzwang
adds now to White's already existing problems.}) ({I must confess that I had
spent some time on my fifth move, even though I was sure it would transpose to
Seirawan's game. The fact is that in one of Yasser's pet lines, 4...Ne7 5.a3
Bxc3+ 6.bxc3 b6, 7.Qg4 is dangerous for if 7...0-0 8.Bg5 Qd7 9.Bd3 Ba6?! 10.
Bxh7!+ Kxh7 11.Qh4+. But then I realised that in the current position my
