1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e5 b6 5. Qg4 {This is a typical Winawer French
queen incursion, aiming to punish Black for leaving the g7-pawn undefended so
soon. But in the 4...b6 system Black has a safe solution to this problem.} Bf8
{Quite a paradoxical position. After 5 moves all of Black's pieces are on
their initial squares. But in the next phase his play is likely to be simple,
as he can combine ...Ne7 with ...Ba6 and ...c7-c5. White's queen may well
remain offside on g4 while the d4-pawn could become vulnerable, since c2-c3 is
not available (yet). In this section we examine a few less popular
continuations for White.} 6. f4 (6. a4 {obviously fights against ...Ba6 but
weakens the b4-square.} Nc6 $1 7. Qd1 (7. Bb5 Bd7 8. Bg5 Nge7 9. Nf3 (9. Nd1 h5
10. Qf4 Ng6 11. Qg3 Be7 12. Bxe7 Ncxe7 13. Bd3 c5 14. c3 b5 15. axb5 cxd4 16.
Nf3 {1/2-1/2, 25)} Nf5 17. Bxf5 exf5 18. cxd4 Bxb5) 9... h6 10. Qh3 Nb4 11. Rc1
a6 12. Be2 c5 $15 {Beliavsky,A (2620)-Petrosian,T (2585) Moscow 1981 (1-0, 77)}
) (7. Nf3 Nb4 8. Kd1 Ne7 9. Ne2 c5 $36 {Roemer,T (2059)-Derichs,R (2295)
Hessen 2017 (0-1, 32)}) 7... Nge7 8. Nf3 {Becerra Rivero,J (2537)-Akobian,V 
(2571) San Diego 2004 (1/2-1/2, 41)} Bb7 9. Be2 (9. Bd3 Nb4 10. Bb5+ c6 11. Be2
Nf5 12. a5 c5 $132) 9... Nf5 10. O-O Be7 11. g4 Nh4 12. Nxh4 Bxh4 13. f4 h6 14.
b3 Qd7 15. Ba3 Be7 16. Bxe7 Qxe7 17. Qd2 f6 $132) (6. Bd3 {justifies} Ba6 {
already.} 7. Nb5 {The only way to question Black's strategy.} ({If} 7. Bxa6
Nxa6 8. a3 Qd7 9. Nge2 c5 10. O-O Ne7 11. Rb1 h5 12. Qf3 Nf5 13. dxc5 Nxc5 $11
{Modi,P-Leskovar,M (2357) ICC (blitz) 2009 (1-0, 50)}) 7... Ne7 (7... c6 $2 8.
Nd6+ Bxd6 9. Qxg7 $18) 8. a4 (8. Nf3 Qd7 9. a4 Ng6 10. h4 h5 11. Qg3 c6 12.
Nd6+ Bxd6 13. exd6 Bxd3 14. cxd3 c5 15. O-O Nc6 $11) 8... Bb7 9. a5 a6 10. Nc3
Nbc6 11. axb6 cxb6 {Black has made progress with his development and the
threat ...Nb4 is unplesant. True, ...c7-c5 is not available anymore, but in
the long run Black can dream of creating a passed pawn on the a-file.} 12. Na2
(12. Nf3 Nb4) (12. Be2 h5) (12. Bf1 Nf5 13. Nf3 Nb4 14. Kd1 Rc8 15. Bd2 b5 16.
Rc1 Qb6) 12... a5 13. c3 Qc8 14. Bg5 Ba6 15. Nc1 h6 16. Bxe7 Nxe7 $11) 6... Ne7
7. Be3 (7. Bd3 Ba6 $11) (7. Nf3 c5 $146 {Since White has delayed his bishop's
development, it makes sense to deviate from the standard ...Ba6. With the
