1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e5 b6 5. a3 {This is the main alternative to 5.
Qg4.} Bf8 {The same reaction as against 5.Qg4. True, White has not committed
his queen now, but a2-a3 is also a small waste of time and a queenside
weakening. In this section we are going to examine some of the minor
alternatives.} 6. Bb5+ {A familiar plan, designed to avoid the bishops'
exchange.} ({The kingside attack based on} 6. h4 {leaves Black free hands in
the centre:} Ne7 7. h5 h6 8. g4 c5 9. f4 Nec6 $11) (6. Bd3 {allows} Ba6 (6...
c5 {is also possible as the bishop is exposed on d3.} 7. Nf3 Nc6 8. Be3 a6 9.
O-O c4 10. Be2 Nge7 $132) 7. Bxa6 Nxa6 $11) (6. b4 {rather plays into Black's
hands:} c5 7. bxc5 bxc5 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Qg4 {Cheparinov,I (2529)-Gallego Eraso,
F (2385) Andorra 2003 (1-0, 39)} Ne7 10. Qxg7 Rg8 11. Qxh7 Qc7 {, with strong
counterplay.}) 6... Bd7 {A useful developing move, even though it is a
deviation from the main plan.} ({In similar situations I have always reacted
with} 6... c6 7. Ba4 {but now I prefer the main line move.}) 7. Bd3 c5 {
The point is that White faces problems consolidating d4.} 8. f4 (8. Qg4 Nc6 (
8... h5 9. Qf4 Nh6 10. dxc5 bxc5 11. Nf3 Nc6 $13 {Comp Hitech-Gulko,B (2605)
Cambridge 1989 (0-1, 69)}) 9. Nf3 Nge7 (9... h5 $5) (9... c4 $5 10. Be2 Nge7)
10. O-O c4 $1 (10... Nxd4 11. Nxd4 cxd4 12. Nb5 Ng6 13. Re1 Qb8 14. h4 a6 15.
Nd6+ Bxd6 16. exd6 $16 {Santo Roman,M (2410)-Seret,J (2440) France 1993 (1/2-1/
2, 70)}) 11. Nb5 {This must have been what Black feared, but it is not that
dangerous.} Nc8 12. Be2 a6 13. Bg5 Be7 14. Bxe7 N6xe7 15. Qxg7 $5 Rg8 16. Qxh7
Bxb5 17. h4 Kd7 $13) 8... Nc6 9. Nf3 Nh6 {As usual after f2-f4, Black has
comfortable development.} 10. O-O ({Preventing ...c4 with} 10. b3 {weakens the
queenside dark squares:} Nxd4 11. Nxd4 cxd4 12. Ne2 Ng4 13. Qd2 f6 14. exf6
Qxf6 15. Bb2 Bc5 16. O-O O-O 17. b4 Qh6 18. h3 Ne3 19. bxc5 bxc5 $44 {Delorme,
A (2415)-Genocchio,D (2440) Pavia 2009 (0-1, 24)}) 10... c4 ({I prefer this
plan over} 10... Nxd4 11. Nxd4 cxd4 {, which seems playable, too.} 12. Ne2 Qh4
(12... Ng4 {Doric,D (2468)-Genocchio,D (2455) Trieste 2009 (1-0, 75)} 13. Qe1)
13. Nxd4 Ng4 14. h3 Nxe5 15. Nxe6 fxe6 16. fxe5 Bc5+ 17. Kh2 Bf2 $13 {Doric,D 
(2468)-Genocchio,D (2455) Trieste 2009 (1-0, 75)}) 11. Be2 a6 12. Kh1 b5 {
It suddenly appears that White has no simple way to carry out g2-g4, which
would leave the h6-knight passive.} 13. Rg1 (13. Be3 Nf5 14. Bf2 h5 $11) (13.
h3 Nf5 $11 {, followed by ...h5.}) (13. Qe1 Qb6 14. Qf2 Ng4 15. Qg1 g6 16. h3
h5 $1 $11) 13... Ng4 14. Qe1 h5 $11 *

