1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e5 b6 5. a3 Bf8 6. f4 {A seemingly aggressive
move, which allows Black to define his plans easier. Apart from the usual
queenside play he has a clear plan of blocking the kingside on the light
squares.} Ne7 {On this square the knight obstructs the bishop, but keeps the
possibility of consolidating the kingside with ...h7-h5 and ...Nf5. Black
should not hurry with the latter though.} (6... Nh6 $5 {From the point of view
of developing speed, this looks best, but on the other hand the knight may be
cut off with h3 and g4.} 7. Be3 (7. Nf3 Ba6 ({I would prefer} 7... c5 $5 {
in the spirit of the main game.}) 8. Bxa6 Nxa6 9. Qd3 Nb8 10. Ne2 {After this
gentle retreat Black gets a wonderful game.} ({Engines once again come up with
an unexpected resource:} 10. g4 $5 Nxg4 11. f5 Nc6 12. h3 Nh6 13. Bxh6 gxh6 14.
O-O-O {White's kingside pressure looks strong, but the extra (doubled) pawn
ensures some control along the g-file. While building up the following
sequence, the computer's optimism gradually decreases, down to the level of
indifference.} Qd7 15. Rhg1 O-O-O 16. Ne2 Kb7 17. Rdf1 Na5 18. Kb1 c5 19. c3
Rc8 20. Nd2 Rc7 {with a fair balance between attack and defence on both wings.}
) 10... c5 11. c3 Nc6 12. h3 c4 13. Qc2 Qd7 14. g4 f5 {Black has achieved
excellent stability on both wings. White's answer only makes things worse.} 15.
exf6 gxf6 16. Ng3 O-O-O 17. Kf2 Nf7 18. Re1 Nd6 $17 {Alekseev,E (2625)-Gulko,B
(2589) Ruschess.com INT 2005 (1-0, 58)}) 7... c5 ({With this concrete move
order, there are no deviations from the positional course after} 7... Ba6 8.
Bxa6 Nxa6 9. Nce2 c5 10. c3 Qd7 11. Nf3 Be7 12. Bf2 c4 13. h3 f5 {The same
pattern as in the aforementioned Gulko game. And White's reaction is the same.}
14. exf6 gxf6 15. Ng3 Nc7 16. f5 {Without this, White would be just
strategically lost.} O-O-O 17. fxe6 Qxe6+ 18. Qe2 Rhg8 19. O-O Qxe2 20. Nxe2
Bd6 21. Bh4 Rde8 22. Rae1 {and now, in Ehlvest,J (2602)-Gulko,B (2597)
Willemstad 2003 (1/2, 47) Black missed a hidden opportunity:} Nf5 $1 23. Bxf6
Bg3 24. Nxg3 Nxg3 25. Rf2 {The intermediate exchange on e8 leaves the
f6-bishop en prise.} Ne4 $17) 8. Nf3 Nc6 ({A similar game of a true classic
took a different course:} 8... Nf5 9. Bf2 Nc6 10. Bb5 Bd7 11. Bxc6 Bxc6 12. Ne2
h5 13. g3 a5 14. Qd2 c4 15. h3 b5 16. Kf1 b4 {As a well known KI specialist,
Bronstein must have been very pleased with this attacking plan. The Mar del
Plata attack structure can be obtained by mirroring this one.} 17. axb4 Bxb4 $3
{Keeping the b-file open for the attack.} 18. c3 Be7 19. Kg2 Kd7 20. Kh2 a4 21.
Ne1 Rb8 22. Ng2 Qg8 23. Ne3 Qh7 24. Ng2 Rb7 25. Ra2 Rhb8 $17 {White is in big
trouble and the next move just makes things worse. Machulsky,A (2390)
-Bronstein,D (2595) Tbilisi 1974 (0-1, 55)}) 9. Qd2 Be7 10. h3 {The critical
move. If White gets to isolate the knight with g2-g4, he will be better.} (10.
Bb5 Bd7 11. h3 Nf5 12. Bf2 {Mahmoud,P (2297)-Ghane Gardeh,S (2374) Mashad 2003
(0-1, 47)} Nfxd4 13. Nxd4 cxd4 14. Bxd4 (14. Bxc6 dxc3 15. Qxc3 Rc8 16. Bxd7+
Qxd7 17. Qd2 Qa4 $36) 14... Nxd4 15. Qxd4 Bh4+ 16. Ke2 O-O $15) 10... Nf5 $1 (
10... cxd4 $6 11. Nxd4 Bh4+ 12. Bf2 Nxd4 13. Qxd4 Nf5 14. Qd2 $14 {Dolmatov,S 
(2550)-Gulko,B (2490) Volgodonsk 1983 (1-0, 27)}) 11. Bf2 Ncxd4 12. Nxd4 Nxd4
13. Bxd4 cxd4 14. Qxd4 (14. Bb5+ Bd7 {would transpose above.}) 14... Bh4+ 15.
Kd1 O-O $15) 7. Be3 h5 8. Bf2 {Played as if inviting my ...Nf5, but I feared
that my knight would be exposed in view of the latent threat g3, h3, g4, so I
constantly refrained from accepting the challenge.} (8. Nf3 Qd7 ({In the lines
with f2-f4, White not only has weakened his light squares even more, but also
spent a valuable tempo. Therefore, Black could consider exchanging the
light-squared bishops without waiting for the f1-bishop to move:} 8... Ba6 $5
9. Bxa6 Nxa6 10. Qd3 Nb8 11. g3 Nf5 12. Bf2 c5 13. O-O-O Nc6) 9. Nh4 Ba6 (9...
g6 $5 {would be a bt more cautious.} 10. Bb5 c6 11. Bd3 Ba6 $11) 10. Bxa6 (10.
f5 $5 Nxf5 11. Nxf5 exf5 12. Qf3 c6 13. Bg5 Be7 14. Bxe7 Kxe7 15. O-O-O g6 {
White surely has compensation for the pawn, but Blacks position looks solid
enough to resist.}) 10... Nxa6 11. Qe2 Nb8 12. O-O g6 13. Bf2 Nbc6 14. g3 Nf5
15. Nf3 Be7 16. Nd1 Na5 17. Qd3 c5 $36 {Welin,M (2251)-Alekseev,V (2400)
Gothenburg 2001 (0-1, 32)}) 8... Qd7 9. Nf3 Ba6 ({As mentioned before, I was
kind of afraid of} 9... Nf5 10. g3 Be7 (10... Ba6 11. Bxa6 Nxa6 12. Qd3 {
Walek, M (2315)-Dziadykiewcz,T (2110) Trinec 1998 (1/2, 102)} Nb8 $1) 11. Qd2 {
followed by h3 and g4 soon. Sharapov,E (2415)-Kornev,A (2486) Tula 2001 (1/2,
42)}) 10. Bxa6 Nxa6 11. Qd3 (11. Qe2 {does not change the character of the
fight greately:} Nb8 12. g3 Nbc6 ({In fact,} 12... Nf5 {is entirely possible.
Here is a long plausible line:} 13. O-O-O c5 14. dxc5 bxc5 15. h3 Nc6 16. g4
hxg4 17. hxg4 Rxh1 18. Rxh1 Nh6 19. Na4 c4 20. Nc5 Qc8 21. g5 Nf5 22. Rh8 Nce7
23. Nd4 Nxd4 24. Bxd4 Qc6 {[%cal Ge7g6,Ge8c8]}) 13. h3 Ng6 14. Be3 Nce7 15.
O-O-O Nf5 16. Bf2 Be7 {Black has gained some tempi to regroup his minor pieces
in the are where he was supposed to be under attack.} 17. Qd2 O-O-O 18. g4 hxg4
19. hxg4 Rxh1 20. Rxh1 Nh6 21. Rg1 Rh8 22. Be3 c6 23. Qd3 Kb7 24. Kb1 {Lanc,A 
(2385)-Mokry,K (2490) Trnava 1985 (1/2, 31). White's position looks more
active, but the game ended in a draw after a few more moves and without any
major events.}) 11... Nb8 12. O-O-O Nbc6 13. h3 $5 {During the game I felt a
great relief when this move was played. I thought it would be just
carelessness, but things are by far more complicated than any of us suspected.}
({I was more worried about} 13. g3 {and planned to use the offered tempo with
such a plan:} Na5 14. h3 (14. Nd2 {defends c4 but takes the knight away from
