1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e5 b6 5. a3 Bf8 6. Nf3 Ne7 7. Bd3 {This
natural developing move allows Black to continue his main plan:} Ba6 8. Bxa6 ({
A critical line is} 8. O-O $5 {, avoiding the loss of time.} Bxd3 9. cxd3 Nf5
10. b4 (10. Ne2 {Brkic,A (2530)-Andreikin,D (2604) Gaziantep 2008 (1-0, 43)} a5
$11 {, preventing the queenside expansion with b2-b4 and planning to block it
with ...a5-a4. For instance:} 11. Bd2 a4 12. b4 axb3 13. Qxb3 Be7 14. a4 {
The only constructive queenside plan.} O-O 15. a5 Nc6 16. axb6 {Advancing the
pawn would doom it after ...Nb8 or turn it into a comfortable target after ...
Ra7 followed by ...Nb8.} cxb6 {Black has no problems to defend the apparently
weak b6-pawn which could also become a dangerous passed pawn.}) 10... a5 11. b5
c5 12. bxc6 Nxc6 13. Nb5 h5 14. Bf4 (14. Qa4 Qd7 15. Bg5 Be7 16. Bxe7 Kxe7 17.
Rfc1 Rhc8 18. Qd1 Kf8 $11) 14... Be7 15. Rc1 Rc8 16. Qd2 Qd7 17. g3 (17. h3 h4)
17... O-O 18. Rb1 (18. a4 Na7 $15) 18... Na7 19. Nxa7 Qxa7 20. h3 b5 21. Rxb5
Nxd4 22. Nxd4 Qxd4 23. Rxa5 Rc3 $11) ({The critical} 8. Nb5 {is examined
separately in the next line.}) 8... Nxa6 9. O-O ({Spending a tempo on
attacking the klnight actually helps it returning to the most favourable route:
} 9. Qe2 Nb8 10. Bg5 Qd7 11. O-O-O a6 12. h4 {Schwartz,J (1676)-Campbell,D 
(1857) Perth 2009 (1-0, 27)} c5 $15) (9. Qd3 {as in Van Leent,D (2201)-Franic,
M (2421) Pula 2009 (1-0, 47) is similar.} Nb8 10. O-O c5 11. Nb5 c4 $1 $132) (
9. Ne2 c5 10. c3 (10. O-O Nc6 11. c3 c4 12. Ng3 Na5 13. Nh5 h6 14. Be3 Qc7 15.
Nd2 O-O-O 16. f4 g6 17. Ng3 h5 {, with wonderful black play due to his
blockade on light squares. We can notice how important the weakening caused by
a2-a3 can be.}) {Tari,A (2597)-Genocchio,D (2419) Gallipoli 2017 (1-0, 48)}
10... Nb8 $1 {Redirecting the knight closer to the weakened light squares.} 11.
O-O (11. b4 a5 $5) 11... c4 12. Ng3 Nbc6 13. Nh5 h6 14. Be3 Na5 15. Nd2 Qc7 16.
f4 O-O-O 17. g4 g6 18. Nf6 h5 19. h3 hxg4 20. hxg4 Bg7 21. Kg2 Kb7 22. Nf3 Bxf6
23. exf6 Nc8 24. Ne5 Nd6 $15) 9... Nb8 $1 {Once again a useful regrouping.} (
9... c5 {, as in Lopez Martinez,J (2481) -Moskalenko,V (2540) Salou 2006 (1/
2-1/2, 28), allows} 10. Nb5 Nc6 11. c4 {with a certain initiative.}) 10. Be3
Nd7 11. Ne2 c5 {The knights are optimally placed now to start play in the
centre.} 12. c4 (12. Re1 c4 {, followed by the usual queenside attack.}) 12...
dxc4 13. dxc5 (13. Qa4 cxd4 14. Nexd4 Nd5 15. Rac1 Bc5 16. Bg5 Qc8 17. Rxc4 Qb7
$11) 13... Nxc5 14. Bxc5 Qxd1 15. Rfxd1 bxc5 16. Rac1 Nd5 {The strong knight
on d5 and White's weaknesses along the b-file compensate for the isolated pawn
on c5.} 17. Nd2 Be7 18. Nxc4 O-O 19. Nc3 Rfd8 20. Ne4 Rab8 21. Rc2 Nb6 22. Ncd6
Bxd6 23. Rxd6 Rxd6 24. Nxd6 (24. exd6 c4) 24... Na4 25. Nc4 g5 $11 *

