1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e5 b6 5. a3 Bf8 6. Nf3 Ne7 7. Bd3 Ba6 8. Nb5 {
I faced this in a game against a very strong opponent. White tries to prevent
the bishops' exchange.} Nf5 $1 {During the game I was not too enthusiastic
about this generally most desirable move, as I feared to expose the knight to
g2-g4, but ulteriour analysis proved it is the best.} ({I preferred the safe
but unambitious} 8... Nc8 9. O-O (9. c4 c6 10. Nc3 dxc4 11. Be2 Ne7 12. Ne4 {
Ochsner,B (2398)-Bromann,T (2452) Svendborg 2016 (1-0, 29)}) 9... Qd7 10. a4 (
10. Nc3 {Played with the hope that my knight would be misplaced on c8.} Bxd3
11. Qxd3 c5 12. Ne2 c4 $5 {I decided to prove that the move ...Nc8 was useful
by bringing the knight one step closer to b6. Normally, Black would need to
think twice before blocking the queenside, but in the game he is actually two
tempi up due to Nc3-b5-c3.} 13. Qd1 b5 $132 {[%cal Gc8b6] followed by ...Nb6,
mainly meaning that White has lost two tempi. In Alekseev,E (2677)-Marin,M 
(2603) Jerusalem 2015 (1-0, 49) I lost only after trying to force matters in
an equal position, tempted by my opponent's time trouble.}) 10... c6 11. Na3
Bxd3 12. Qxd3 a5 13. c3 $14 {Black's counterplay does not seem easy to
organize.}) 9. g4 {White can attack the knight in several other moments.} (9.
a4 c6 10. g4 Nh6 $1 {With the d6-square vulnerable this is forced.} 11. Bxh6
gxh6 12. Nc3 Bxd3 13. Qxd3 c5 {Black has counterplay on both wings, as his
double pawns are not weaker than the g4-pawn.} 14. Ne2 (14. Qb5+ Nd7 $11) (14.
h3 Bg7 15. Ne2 O-O 16. c3 f6 $11) 14... Nc6 15. c3 h5 $1 {Fighting against the
blockade on the light squares with Nf4-h5.} (15... Qc7 16. Nf4 O-O-O 17. O-O
$14) 16. g5 (16. h3 hxg4 17. hxg4 Be7 18. Rxh7 Kd7 19. Kd2 c4 20. Qc2 Qg8 $132
{with excellent counterplay for the pawn, as the white king is a bit insecure
and the g4-pawn hanging. On the contrary, Black's king is absolutely safe.}) (
16. gxh5 Bh6 $132) 16... Qc7 17. Nf4 O-O-O 18. O-O (18. Nxh5 $6 cxd4 19. cxd4
$6 Nb4) 18... Be7 19. h4 c4 20. Qc2 h6 21. g6 fxg6 22. Nxe6 (22. Nxg6 Rhg8 23.
Kh1 Bf8 24. Rg1 Qf7 25. Rg3 Ne7 26. Nxe7+ Bxe7 $132) 22... Qd7 23. Nxd8 Qg4+
24. Kh2 Qf4+ {with a perpetual.}) (9. O-O c6 10. g4 (10. Nc3 Bxd3 11. cxd3 Nd7
12. Ne2 c5 $11) 10... Bxb5 (10... Nh6 {is also possible:} 11. Bxh6 gxh6 12. Nc3
Rg8 $132) 11. gxf5 Be7 12. Bxb5 cxb5 13. Qd3 Qd7 14. fxe6 fxe6 15. Kh1 Nc6 16.
Rg1 (16. Qxb5 Nxe5) 16... g6 17. c3 (17. Rg3 b4) (17. Qxb5 Nxe5) 17... Na5 18.
Bh6 O-O-O $11) 9... Ne7 $1 {Black agrees on losing two tempi as g2-g4 did not
make White's position more appealing.} (9... Nh6 {is less indicated in this
concrete position as White has not weakend his queenside and can safely castle
long.} 10. Bxh6 gxh6 11. Nc3 Bxd3 12. Qxd3 Qd7 13. O-O-O Nc6 14. Nd2 $14 {
Mingarro Carceller,S (2255)-Fernandez Gil,R (2083) Mislata 2015 (1-0, 23)}) 10.
Be3 ({The kingside attack with} 10. h4 {is too slow:} Bb7 11. h5 a6 12. Nc3 c5
$132) 10... Bb7 11. b4 (11. Qd2 a6 12. Nc3 c5 13. dxc5 $6 d4 $1) (11. Qe2 a6
12. Nc3 Nd7 13. Nd1 c5 14. c3 Nc6 {Opening the queen's communication with the
kingside and clearing the f8-bishop's path.} ({Less good is} 14... h5 15. Ng5
$1) 15. O-O h5 {Now this is playable.} 16. Ng5 cxd4 17. Nxe6 Qe7 18. Nxd4 hxg4
$13) 11... a6 12. Nc3 c5 13. bxc5 ({White fails to maintain his stability
after the other possible pawn grabbing:} 13. dxc5 bxc5 14. Bxc5 Nd7 15. Bd4 Nc6
16. Qe2 h5 17. g5 Nxd4 18. Nxd4 Qxg5 $15) 13... bxc5 14. dxc5 Ng6 15. O-O Nd7
16. Rb1 Bc6 $11 {Black will soon retrieve the pawn, retaining the better
structure.} *

