{[#]White's last move, 12.Ng3, prepares to continue the pawn attack with f5.
What would you do?} 12... h4 $1 {By driving the knight away from g3 Black
ensures himself against f4-f5 for at least a while, sufficient for him to
start his counterplay.} (12... hxg4 13. hxg4 Rxh1 14. Qxh1 $14) 13. Nh5 (13.
Nge2 Na5 14. O-O-O (14. b3 f6 15. O-O-O Nc4 $5 16. bxc4 $2 dxc4 17. d5 Nxd5)
14... Nc4 15. Bf2 f6 $5 $11) 13... Ng8 $1 {Defending f6 in order to prepare
the next move.} 14. O-O-O (14. f5 exf5 15. gxf5 Nge7 16. f6 Qf5 {with strong
counterplay.}) 14... g6 15. Nf6 Nxf6 16. exf6 Na5 $11 {[%cal Ga5c4,Gc4d6,Gd6e4]
The knight is heading for e4 via c4-d6.} 17. f5 $6 exf5 18. gxf5 Qxf5 19. Qxf5+
gxf5 20. Bd3 Nc4 21. Bxf5+ Kb8 22. Bf4 Bh6 $15 {Black's good control in the
centre and the weakness of White's kingside pawns, make Black's play
preferable, Sermier,G (2366)-Moskalenko,V (2569) Sitges 2008 (0-1, 36)} *

