{[#]Black has an active queenside position but the just played 20.Nxf7 changed
the character of the position. How would you evaluate White's piece sacrifice?
} 20... Kxf7 {Black must accept the sacrifice, of course, and with careful
play he should be doing reasonably well.} 21. f5 g5 $1 {The only move
maintaining the position balanced.} ({It makes no sense to clear files for
White's attack:} 21... gxf5 $2 22. gxf5 Rag8 23. Nf4 (23. f6 Bf8 24. Nf4 $18)
23... Rh6 24. Rg1 Rgh8 25. f6 $18 {Hjartarson,J (2550)-Vaganian,R (2585)
Bayern 1991 (1-0, 28)}) 22. f6 (22. fxe6+ Ke8 {extinguished White's attack.})
22... Bf8 (22... Bb4 {[%cal Ga8g8] is an interesting alternative. Black keeps
the possibility of consolidating with ...Rag8, while after} 23. c3 Bf8 {
[%csl Rc3] he would have a target on c3. For instance if} 24. Nf4 {he can
accept the second sacrifice:} gxf4 25. g5 Ke8 26. g6 Kd7 27. Rxf4 b4 $1 28. g7
Rg8 29. gxf8=Q Rgxf8 {with adequate counterplay.}) 23. Nf4 Rh6 ({In the
absence of the target on c3,} 23... gxf4 24. g5 {more or less wins.}) 24. Qf3 {
/\Nh3} a4 25. Kb1 (25. Nh3 $2 a3 26. b3 Nxe5 27. Nxg5+ Ke8) 25... Bb4 $1 {
[%cal Ga8g8] Preparing ...Rg8.} 26. c3 Ba5 27. Nh3 Rg8 28. Bxc4 bxc4 29. Qe3
Rhg6 $11 {White has excellent compensation for the piece but this should only
be enough for a positional draw.} *

