{[#]Due to his control on the light squares, Black would have a dream position
if it was not for his weaknesses on e6 and g6. How can he deal with this
situation?} 17... Kb8 18. h4 (18. Qxe6 $2 Bc8 {[%csl Re6] traps the queen.})
18... Bc8 19. Nf4 g5 $1 {Opening the h-file for Black's counterplay. White
should not be allowed to consolidate with Nxg6.} 20. hxg5 hxg5 21. Nxg5 Rh6 22.
Nf3 (22. Nfh3 Qg6 23. Qg3 Qf5 {also offers Black enough activity for the pawn.}
) 22... g5 ({More energetic than} 22... Qf7 23. Nh3 {Comp Kallisto-Bronstein,D
(2400) The Hague 1994 (0-1, 40)}) 23. Nh3 (23. Nxg5 Bxg5 24. Qxg5 Qh8 $17 25.
Nh3 $2 Rxh3 26. gxh3 Rg8 $19) 23... Qg6 24. Nfxg5 Rdh8 25. f4 a5 {Preparing
the bishop's activation as e6 is safely defended now.} 26. Qe2 Ka7 {[%cal
Gc6d8,Gd8f7] With excellent compensation for the pawns due to White's poor
coordination and the weaknesses on light squares. Black could consider ...
Nd8-f7 soon, to shake White's kingside fortress.} *

